subject: Exclude not used schemas
commitMessage:
Exclude not used schemas

Created a list of all used schemas, and a few being added for use in reviews
now. Exclude all other schemas.

Developers if they wish to use a new schema will have to add it to this
list and rerun update_schemas.py.

131kB of flash space saved.  Good work.
Does it make more sense to invert this into an "include list"  Then, when we add new schema packs, we wont have to update this at the same time.
I can. Is it too much of a pain to ask people to modify this and rerun this every time they need to include a schema..? I really don't want people adding/modify schemas by hand.

For fear of having someone break it because they don't know it's there?  I wonder if there's a way we could force that a little, like generate an hpp file with definitions for all the odata.ids that are allowed, so that if they try to add a new schema with an id we don't ship, they get a compiler error and they know they have to update the list.

I'm thinking out loud at this point.

Overall, I think I'm ok with having to update the list when we add a new schema, it's just a little bit of lore we'll have to remember, and if we mess it up, CI should catch it.
Do we need a README update to document this new process?
Added a sentence to Redfish.md
